e fibrosis","Granulation tissue"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGastric ulcers typically show four distinct histological zones from superficial to deep:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellular debris\u003C/strong\u003E and necrotic material at the surface\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZone of acute inflammation with neutrophils\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulation tissue\u003C/strong\u003E containing new blood vessels and fibroblasts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDense fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E (scarring) at the base\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloid deposits\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium deposits\u003C/strong\u003E are not typical features of gastric ulcers. Granulation tissue is particularly prominent in actively healing ulcers and represents the body\u0027s attempt at repair through neovascularisation and fibroblast proliferation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastric ulcers show four distinct histological zones: necrotic debris, acute inflammation, granulation tissue, and fibrosis/scarring","Granulation tissue is a hallmark finding in healing ulcers, containing new blood vessels and fibroblasts"],"references":["Dixon MF. Pathology of Gastritis and Peptic Ulceration. In: Mobley HLT, Mendz GL, Hazell SL, editors. Helicobacter pylori: Physiology and Genetics. Washington (DC): ASM Press; 2001. Chapter 38. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2461/","Woolf A, Rose R. Gastric Ulcer. [Updated 2023 Nov 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537128/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (